cell("markdown","# Algorithms 11: Multivariable Gradient Descent\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Understand gradients as vectors of partial derivatives\n2. Apply the multivariable update rule computationally\n3. Optimize functions of two or more variables\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 10\n**Estimated time:** 60 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapter 11"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### Multivariable Gradient Descent\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 11:* Multivariable gradient descent is similar to single-variable, except we replace the scalar derivative $f'(x)$ with the **gradient vector** $\\nabla f(\\vec{x})$.\n\n$$\\vec{x}_{n+1} = \\vec{x}_n - \\alpha \\nabla f(\\vec{x}_n)$$\n\nIf $f$ is a function of $(x, y)$, the gradient is a vector containing the partial derivatives:\n$$\\nabla f(x, y) = \\left\\langle \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}, \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y} \\right\\rangle$$\n\nFor example, if $f(x, y) = x \\sin(y) + x^2$:\n- $\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x} = \\sin(y) + 2x$\n- $\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y} = x \\cos(y)$\n\nOur update rule becomes two simultaneous equations:\n$$x_{n+1} = x_n - \\alpha (\\sin(y_n) + 2x_n)$$\n$$y_{n+1} = y_n - \\alpha (x_n \\cos(y_n))$$"),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. What does the vector $\\nabla f(x,y)$ geometrically represent on a 3D surface $z = f(x,y)$?\n2. If $\\nabla f(x,y) = \\langle 0, 0 \\rangle$, what do we know about the point $(x,y)$?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. It points in the direction of steepest *ascent* (steepest uphill slope). That's why we subtract it to go downhill.\n2. It is a critical point (a local minimum, local maximum, or saddle point). The surface is completely flat there.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Partial Derivatives\nGiven $f(x, y) = (x - 1)^2 + 3y^2$.\n1. Find $\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}$\n2. Find $\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}$\n\n*(Work it out on paper, then check the code below)*"),
