cell("markdown","### Chalkboard Defense\nIf one partial derivative $\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}$ is generally huge (e.g. 1000) and another $\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}$ is tiny (e.g. 0.01), why might standard gradient descent struggle? (Hint: think about the single learning rate $\\alpha$).\n\n<details><summary>💡 Sketch</summary>\nBecause we use a single learning rate $\\alpha$, a value that is small enough to keep $x$ from diverging might be so microscopic that $y$ takes millions of iterations to converge. This is why advanced optimizers (like Adam) maintain separate, adaptive learning rates for every single variable!\n</details>\n\n---\n📚 **Next:** Algorithms 12 (Basic Sorting)")
