cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### $O(n^2)$ Sorting Algorithms\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 12:* There are many methods for sorting arrays. The simplest are Selection, Bubble, and Insertion sort. They all take $O(n^2)$ time.\n\n- **Selection Sort:** Find the minimum element in the remaining array, and move it to the end of the sorted array.\n- **Bubble Sort:** Repeatedly swap adjacent elements if they are out of order. In each pass, the largest remaining element \"bubbles\" to the top. Stop when a full pass makes 0 swaps.\n- **Insertion Sort:** Take the next out-of-order element and swap it backwards until it sits in its correct sorted position among the already-processed elements.\n\n### Counting Sort: An $O(N+K)$ Alternative\nCounting sort does not compare elements! It counts occurrences of each number, then generates a new array directly from the counts. It is extremely fast but can use a massive amount of memory if the range of numbers is very large."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. Why is Bubble Sort $O(n^2)$?\n2. If an array contains the numbers `[1, 1000000]`, why is Counting Sort a terrible idea?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. In the worst case (a reverse-sorted array), it takes $n$ passes, and each pass performs $n$ comparisons/swaps. $n \\times n = n^2$.\n2. Counting sort requires a `counts` array of size `max - min + 1`. You would allocate an array of 1,000,000 integers just to sort 2 numbers!\n</details>"),
