cell("code","def selection_sort_inplace(arr):\n    a = list(arr)\n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    return a"),
cell("markdown","### Chalkboard Defense\nExplain why Insertion Sort is extraordinarily fast ($O(N)$) if the input array is *already sorted*, whereas Selection Sort remains $O(N^2)$ even if the input is perfectly sorted.\n\n<details><summary>💡 Sketch</summary>\nIn Insertion Sort, if the array is already sorted, the inner `while` loop (which swaps backwards) never executes. The outer loop just does 1 check per element and moves on, taking $O(N)$ time.\nSelection Sort, however, blindly scans the entire remaining array to find the minimum *every single time*, regardless of order. It does $\\frac{N(N-1)}{2}$ comparisons no matter what.\n</details>\n\n---\n📚 **Next:** Algorithms 13 (Advanced Sorting: Merge & Quicksort)")
