cell("markdown","# Algorithms 13: Advanced Sorting\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Understand \"Divide and Conquer\" algorithms\n2. Implement Merge Sort recursively\n3. Implement Quicksort recursively\n4. Understand $O(n \\log n)$ time complexity\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 12\n**Estimated time:** 90 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapter 13"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The Need for Speed\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 13:* With an average-case time complexity of $O(n \\log n)$, Merge Sort and Quicksort are generally faster than selection, bubble, and insertion sort. And unlike counting sort, they don't blow up in memory on large numbers.\n\n### Merge Sort (Divide & Conquer)\n1. Break the array in half.\n2. Recursively call Merge Sort on each half.\n3. Merge the two sorted halves back together.\nBase Case: Arrays of length 0 or 1 are already sorted.\n\n### Quicksort\n1. Pick a random `pivot` element.\n2. Split the rest of the array into three arrays: elements `< pivot`, `== pivot`, and `> pivot`.\n3. Recursively call Quicksort on the `<` array and `>` array.\n4. Concatenate the sorted `<` array, the `==` array, and the sorted `>` array."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. If we have two sorted arrays `A=[2, 5]` and `B=[3, 8]`, how do we merge them in $O(N)$ time?\n2. What happens to Quicksort if we accidentally always pick the absolute largest element as our pivot?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. Look at the first element of both (2 vs 3). 2 is smaller, pop it. Then look at 5 vs 3. 3 is smaller, pop it. Repeat until empty.\n2. The `<` array gets everything, and the `>` array gets nothing. We only reduced the problem size by 1! The time complexity degrades to $O(n^2)$.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: The Merge Helper\nWrite a function that takes two *already sorted* arrays and merges them into one sorted array in $O(N)$ time. \nDo not just concatenate and call `.sort()`! Use two pointers (or `pop(0)`)."),
